ffers a range of Renminbi and foreign currency products and services to multinational and local companies, Chinese residents and foreign nationals. Stephen Bird, Chief Executive Officer, Citi Asia Pacific and Andrew Au, Chief Executive Officer of Citi China, attended the opening ceremony.","month":"05","year":"2011","publishDate":"May 11, 2011","siteId":"citigpa","type":"insights","title":"Citi Expands China Network, Opens Branch in Nanjing","category":"PRESS RELEASE","url":"https://www.citigroup.com/global/news/press-release/2011/citi-expands-china-network-opens-branch-in-nanjing","tags":["Press Release Migration","Consumer Banking"]},{"summary":"Emerging market (EM) investors have begun to worry about the end of the second round of quantitative easing (QE2) in mid-year. The concern has been that higher U.S. yields would boost the cost of capital in EMs and threaten equity valuations. Yet recently, markets imply that the risk is in the other direction -- economic worries in the U.S. and falling Treasury yields. While our Macro Strategy team expects yields to fall near-term as they did at the end of QE1, our economists forecast US 10-year yields to rebound to 3.6% by Q4, a fairly modest increase of 40-50 basis points (bp) from current levels. Such a yield increase should pose little risk to emerging markets and would present a positive backdrop for EM equities.","month":"05","author.displayName":["Geoffrey Dennis"],"year":"2011","publishDate":"May 11, 2011","siteId":"citigpa","type":"insights","title":"The end of QE2 and emerging market equities.","category":"PERSPECTIVES","author.jobTitle":["Global Emerging Markets Strategist"],"url":"https://www.citigroup.com/global/news/perspective/2011/the-end-of-qe2-and-emerging-market-equities","tags":["Perspective Migration"]},{"month":"05","author.displayName":["Citi"],"year":"2011","publishDate":"May 11, 2011","siteId":"citigpa","type":"insights","title":"\"Thanks, Mom!\"","category":"PERSPECTIVES","author.jobTitle":["Citi"],"url":"https://www.citigroup.com/global/news/perspective/2011/thanks-mom","tags":["Perspective Migration"]},{"month":"05","author.displayName":["Citi"],"year":"2011","publishDate":"May 11, 2011","siteId":"citigpa","type":"insights","title":"Citi's Egypt analysis in the FT.","category":"PERSPECTIVES","author.jobTitle":["Citi"],"url":"https://www.citigroup.com/global/news/perspective/2011/citis-egypt-analysis-in-the-ft","tags":["Perspective Migration"]},{"summary":"Buenos Aires – Citi Argentina introduced the Citi MasterCard Women and Citi AAdvantage Black Mastercard credit cards, both featuring the American Airlines miles program. The cards are targeted to women.","month":"05","year":"2011","publishDate":"May 10, 2011","siteId":"citigpa","type":"insights","title":"Citi Argentina Introduces Credit Cards Targeted to Women","category":"PRESS RELEASE","url":"https://www.citigroup.com/global/news/press-release/2011/citi-argentina-introduces-credit-cards-targeted-to-women","tags":["Press Release Migration","Consumer Banking"]},{"summary":"Last year, in one landmark transaction, Citi Community Capital (\"Citi\") helped the New York City Housing Authority (\"NYCHA\") secure over $900 million in financing to help restore NYCHA's financial health, begin much-needed rehabilitations at 21 public housing developments throughout New York City and create hundreds of construction jobs on shovel-ready projects. The upgrades will include brick work, façade and roof repairs, elevator replacement, entrance renovations and heating upgrades in 20,000 units, improving the quality of the homes of more than 46,000 low-income New Yorkers.","image":"638e3071a3c47c530c0a5caa","year":"2011","publishDate":"May 10, 2011","type":"insights","title":"Financing New York City public housing development.","author.jobTitle":["Citi Community Capital"],"url":"https://www.citigroup.com/global/news/perspective/2011/financing-new-york-city-public-housing-development","tags":["Perspective Migration"],"month"